National Security Advisor Jake Sullivan of the United States met with National Security Secretariat Secretary General Akiba Takeo of Japan and National Security Office Director Kim Sung-han of the Republic of Korea (ROK) on September 1, 2022. The meeting took place at the Headquarters of the United States Indo-Pacific Command in Honolulu, Hawaii. The main focus of the meeting was to address protecting and advancing the rules-based international order. 

During the meeting, they discussed their joint commitment to peace and stability across the Taiwan Strait. They also condemned the Democratic People's Republic of Korea's (DPRK) continued development of its ballistic missile and weapons of mass destruction programs, as well as Russian aggression in Ukraine. 

The United States reaffirmed its ironclad alliance commitments to both Japan and the ROK. This includes the commitment to extended deterrence for both countries. The importance of bilateral ties and trilateral cooperation for the security and prosperity of their citizens, the region, and the world was emphasized. 

The national security advisors also discussed ways to strengthen their ties, based on their shared vision for a free and open Indo-Pacific.